phases.best_practices:
SOLID and refactor guidance for phases[0]:

Single Responsibility. EmitMutationJson owns rendering the mutation
response envelope and nothing else. The InAckOnly bool selects between
two well-defined output shapes. Do not introduce a third shape, a
partial-ack mode, or a verbosity enum; that is scope creep beyond P1.

Open/Closed. EmitMutationJson becomes "open for extension, closed for
modification" in the sense that adding a new response shape later is
additive (new schema constant + new branch). This phase adds exactly
one branch, the --ack-only shape. Future phases can add more if a
concrete need arises.

Domain type over primitive bool. The executor may choose to represent
the response shape selector as a primitive bool (InAckOnly) or as a
typed enum class EMutationResponseShape { FullV1, AckOnly }. Either is
acceptable at this phase's scale; prefer the enum if more shapes are
expected in the same release. If the project has only these two
shapes for the forseeable future, bool is fine.

No stringly-typed if-chain. The shape selector is a single binary
branch. Do not grow a chain like:

    if (Shape == "v1")  { ... }
    else if (Shape == "ack") { ... }
    else if (Shape == "quiet") { ... }

If a third shape lands, convert to an enum class at that point; the
registration-table escape hatch (std::array<FEmitEntry>) is overkill
for two branches.

No raw ownership changes. This phase touches only stack-local values
and references to Options structs. No std::make_unique, no
std::make_shared, no raw new.

No std::regex. The option parser uses exact-token comparison
(InToken == "--ack-only") - same as every existing parser clause.

No goto. Structured control flow throughout.

Anti-Pattern negative example for regression guard (this block is
documented as rejected; the snippet lint must skip it per the
// BAD: marker).

```cpp
// BAD: REJECTED stringly-typed dispatch for response shape.
// Do not reintroduce this pattern if more shapes are added.
void EmitMutationJsonBad(const std::string &InShape, ...)
{
    if (InShape == "v1") {
        // ... full envelope ...
    } else if (InShape == "ack") {
        // ... compact envelope ...
    } else if (InShape == "quiet") {
        // ... even shorter envelope ...
    } else if (InShape == "silent") {
        // ... no envelope at all ...
    }
}
```

The accepted shape for this phase is a single InAckOnly bool. If
future phases add shapes, convert to:

```cpp
enum class EMutationResponseShape { FullV1, AckOnly };

void EmitMutationJson(..., EMutationResponseShape InShape);
```

Not:

```cpp
// Still BAD in the future: string tag passed through the whole
// call chain instead of a typed enum.
void EmitMutationJson(..., const std::string &InShape);
```

Naming conventions (from NAMING.md):

- kMutationAckSchema: lowercase `k` prefix, PascalCase body.
- mbAckOnly: `mb` prefix for boolean member.
- InAckOnly: `In` prefix for input parameter.
- EMutationResponseShape: `E` prefix for enum class, PascalCase body.

Memory discipline. No heap allocation added in this phase. Every new
field is a value type. No smart pointers, no raw pointers, no
ownership transfer.

Diagnostics. No std::cerr usage added in this phase. The --ack-only
branch emits strictly to std::cout as the existing default branch
does.

Testing discipline. Every test in Test/UniPlanTestMutation.cpp that
covers the v1 shape gains a parallel ack-only assertion. The
byte-identical-bundle test is the load-bearing invariant; if that
fails, the flag has leaked into the mutation path and must be rooted
out before landing.

Validator interaction. Post-mutation, the bundle content is identical
regardless of the flag. Every validator keeps emitting the same issue
set. Do not skip validate in the test suite under --ack-only; the
goal is the flag does not change bundle content, and a failing
validate run is the regression signal.

